      <!-- S1 -->
      <section class="article-section fade-up" id="intro">
        <span class="section-tag">Context</span>
        <h2>Why Injections? The Gap Between Pain Tablets and Surgery</h2>

        <p>For patients with moderate to advanced knee or hip arthritis, there exists an uncomfortable middle ground: oral pain medications are no longer providing sufficient relief, but the condition has not yet reached the severity that would justify joint replacement surgery. It is in this clinical space — often lasting months or years — that <strong>intra-articular injections become highly relevant</strong>.</p>

        <p>Injections deliver medication directly into the joint space, bypassing the digestive system entirely. This allows for a much higher local concentration of the therapeutic agent at the site of pain and inflammation, with significantly reduced systemic side effects compared to long-term oral NSAIDs.</p>

        <div class="pull-quote">
          <p>The right injection at the right time can meaningfully restore function and quality of life — but the wrong one can accelerate the very damage you are trying to slow.</p>
          <cite>— Dr. Sarish Sharma, MS Orthopaedics</cite>
        </div>

        <p>The two most frequently offered options are <strong>Hyaluronic Acid (HA)</strong> injections — also called viscosupplementation or joint lubrication therapy — and <strong>Corticosteroid (Cortisone)</strong> injections. These are not interchangeable. They target entirely different mechanisms of joint pain, work over different timescales, carry different risk profiles, and are appropriate for different patient profiles. Understanding the distinction is essential before consenting to either.</p>
      </section>

      <div class="section-divider"><div class="divider-icon">💉</div></div>

      <!-- S2 -->
      <section class="article-section fade-up" id="how-they-work">
        <span class="section-tag">The Science</span>
        <h2>How Each Injection <em>Actually</em> Works</h2>

        <div class="inject-cards">
          <div class="inject-card ic-teal">
            <span class="ic-emoji">💧</span>
            <div class="ic-name">Hyaluronic Acid</div>
            <div class="ic-also">Also called: Viscosupplementation · Joint Gel · Synvisc · Durolane</div>
            <ul class="ic-points">
              <li>Hyaluronic acid is a naturally occurring substance found in healthy joint fluid (synovial fluid)</li>
              <li>In arthritic joints, HA concentration drops — causing friction, reduced cushioning, and pain</li>
              <li>Injected HA temporarily restores the viscoelastic properties of joint fluid</li>
              <li>Acts as both lubricant (reduces bone-on-bone friction) and shock absorber</li>
              <li>May also stimulate the joint's own HA production over time</li>
              <li>Has mild anti-inflammatory properties through cytokine modulation</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="inject-card ic-gold">
            <span class="ic-emoji">🔥</span>
            <div class="ic-name">Cortisone</div>
            <div class="ic-also">Also called: Corticosteroid · Steroid injection · Methylprednisolone · Triamcinolone</div>
            <ul class="ic-points">
              <li>Cortisone is a synthetic version of cortisol — the body's own stress hormone</li>
              <li>Works by powerfully suppressing the immune and inflammatory response inside the joint</li>
              <li>Reduces swelling, heat, and chemical pain signals within days</li>
              <li>Does not restore joint fluid or cartilage — purely targets inflammation</li>
              <li>Highly effective when inflammation is the dominant driver of pain</li>
              <li>Effect is temporary — does not slow disease progression</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3>The Key Conceptual Difference</h3>
        <p>Think of it this way: <strong>Hyaluronic acid is a structural intervention</strong> — it tries to restore the mechanical environment of the joint. <strong>Cortisone is a chemical intervention</strong> — it suppresses the inflammatory signals that cause pain. One lubricates; the other quiets. A patient with significant cartilage loss and mechanical friction benefits most from HA. A patient with a hot, swollen joint driven by acute synovitis benefits most from cortisone.</p>
      </section>

      <div class="section-divider"><div class="divider-icon">⚖️</div></div>

      <!-- S3 -->
      <section class="article-section fade-up" id="comparison">
        <span class="section-tag">Head to Head</span>
        <h2>Side-by-Side Comparison</h2>

        <table class="big-compare">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Factor</th>
              <th>💧 Hyaluronic Acid</th>
              <th>🔥 Cortisone</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Mechanism</td>
              <td>Lubricates & cushions the joint, restores synovial fluid viscosity</td>
              <td>Suppresses joint inflammation & immune response</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Onset of Relief</td>
              <td>Gradual — 2 to 6 weeks <span class="win-badge">Slower</span></td>
              <td>Fast — often within 2 to 5 days <span class="win-badge gold-badge">Faster</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Duration of Effect</td>
              <td>6 months to 1 year or more <span class="win-badge">Longer</span></td>
              <td>4 to 12 weeks <span class="win-badge gold-badge">Shorter</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Number of Sessions</td>
              <td>1–3 injections (sometimes a course of 3–5 weekly)</td>
              <td>Single injection; can repeat with restrictions</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Best For</td>
              <td>Mild to moderate osteoarthritis; long-term management</td>
              <td>Acute flare-ups; significant joint swelling; pre-procedure relief</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Effect on Cartilage</td>
              <td>Protective — may slow cartilage degradation <span class="win-badge">Better</span></td>
              <td>Potentially damaging with repeated use <span class="win-badge gold-badge">Caution</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Effect on Blood Sugar</td>
              <td>Minimal / none <span class="win-badge">Safer for diabetics</span></td>
              <td>Can spike blood sugar for 1–2 weeks <span class="win-badge gold-badge">Caution in diabetes</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Frequency Limit</td>
              <td>Can be repeated annually with fewer restrictions</td>
              <td>Maximum 3–4 times per year in any one joint</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Cost</td>
              <td>Higher per session</td>
              <td>Lower per session</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Evidence Strength</td>
              <td>Strong for moderate OA, variable for severe OA</td>
              <td>Strong for acute inflammation; limited long-term data</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Pre-surgery use</td>
              <td>Not recommended within 3 months before surgery</td>
              <td>Not recommended within 3 months before surgery</td>
