      </section>

      <div class="section-divider"><div class="divider-icon">🎯</div></div>

      <!-- S4 -->
      <section class="article-section fade-up" id="who-is-right">
        <span class="section-tag">Patient Matching</span>
        <h2>Who Is Each Injection Right For?</h2>

        <p>The decision is not simply about which is 'better' — it is about which is more appropriate for <em>your specific situation</em>. These are the clinical profiles where each injection tends to perform best.</p>

        <div class="decision-grid">
          <div class="decision-card dc-teal">
            <div class="dc-head">💧 Choose Hyaluronic Acid If...</div>
            <ul class="dc-list">
              <li>You have mild to moderate osteoarthritis (Grade 1–3 on X-ray)</li>
              <li>Your pain is chronic and ongoing, not an acute flare</li>
              <li>You have tried cortisone before but effects wore off quickly</li>
              <li>You have Type 2 diabetes or need to avoid blood sugar spikes</li>
              <li>You want longer-lasting relief with fewer repeat injections</li>
              <li>You are trying to delay joint replacement surgery</li>
              <li>Your joint fluid is reduced but not severely inflamed</li>
              <li>You are under 65 with an active lifestyle to protect</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-card dc-gold">
            <div class="dc-head">🔥 Choose Cortisone If...</div>
            <ul class="dc-list">
              <li>Your joint is acutely swollen, hot, and inflamed</li>
              <li>You need rapid relief — an upcoming event, travel, or procedure</li>
              <li>You have severe arthritis with significant synovitis</li>
              <li>You are preparing for physiotherapy and need pain reduction first</li>
              <li>You've had good results from cortisone previously and relapsed</li>
              <li>Budget is a significant constraint in your treatment decision</li>
              <li>You are awaiting surgery and need temporary symptom control</li>
              <li>Inflammatory arthritis (rheumatoid) is contributing to your pain</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="note-box">
          <div class="wb-icon">💡</div>
          <p><strong>Combination Approach:</strong> In some patients, a cortisone injection is given first to rapidly reduce acute inflammation and swelling, followed several weeks later by a hyaluronic acid injection to provide longer-term lubrication and structural support. This staged protocol is used selectively and only when clinically appropriate.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="section-divider"><div class="divider-icon">⚠️</div></div>

      <!-- S5 -->
      <section class="article-section fade-up" id="risks">
        <span class="section-tag">Honest Picture</span>
        <h2>Risks & Side Effects: What You Must Know</h2>

        <div class="info-card teal">
          <div class="info-card-title">
            <div class="info-card-icon icon-teal">💧</div>
            Hyaluronic Acid — Risks & Side Effects
          </div>
          <p style="font-size:0.9rem; margin-bottom:12px;">Generally considered very safe. Serious complications are rare.</p>
          <ul style="list-style:none; display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:10px;">
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.87rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--teal); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Injection site reaction</strong> — temporary swelling, warmth, or mild pain for 24–72 hours (10–20% of patients)</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.87rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--teal); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Pseudo-septic reaction</strong> — rare acute inflammatory flare (1–2%) requiring drainage; not a true infection</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.87rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--teal); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Infection</strong> — very rare (&lt;0.01%) if performed with strict sterile technique</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.87rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--teal); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Allergy</strong> — rare; patients allergic to avian products should confirm non-animal-derived HA formulations are used</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.87rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--teal); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>No effect</strong> — some patients (especially with severe Grade 4 OA) may not respond; this is a treatment limitation, not a complication</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card gold" style="margin-top:20px;">
          <div class="info-card-title">
            <div class="info-card-icon icon-gold">🔥</div>
            Cortisone — Risks & Side Effects
          </div>
          <p style="font-size:0.9rem; margin-bottom:12px;">More potent anti-inflammatory effect comes with a more significant risk profile, especially with repeated use.</p>
          <ul style="list-style:none; display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:10px;">
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.87rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--gold); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Blood sugar elevation</strong> — can raise glucose levels significantly for 5–14 days; requires close monitoring in diabetics</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.87rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--gold); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Cartilage degradation</strong> — repeated cortisone injections (more than 3–4 per year) are associated with accelerated cartilage loss; this is a major clinical concern</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.87rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--gold); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Tendon weakening</strong> — steroid near tendons increases rupture risk; requires post-injection activity restriction</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.87rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--gold); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Skin & fat atrophy</strong> — depigmentation and thinning of skin at injection site (more common with repeated superficial injections)</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.87rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--gold); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Infection risk</strong> — suppresses local immune response; low but real risk of joint sepsis</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.87rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--gold); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Steroid flare</strong> — paradoxical worsening of joint pain 12–24 hours post-injection in ~10% of patients; usually self-limiting within 48 hours</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="warning-box">
          <div class="wb-icon">🚨</div>
          <p><strong>Critical Warning for Diabetic Patients:</strong> Cortisone injections can cause dangerous hyperglycaemia (high blood sugar) lasting up to two weeks. If you have Type 1 or Type 2 diabetes, discuss this explicitly with your doctor before any steroid injection and plan for increased blood sugar monitoring post-procedure. Hyaluronic acid is generally the preferred alternative in this population.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="section-divider"><div class="divider-icon">🧠</div></div>

      <!-- S6 -->
      <section class="article-section fade-up" id="myths">
        <span class="section-tag">Setting the Record Straight</span>
        <h2>Common Myths About Joint Injections — Debunked</h2>

        <div class="myth-list">
          <div class="myth-item">
            <div class="myth-row">
              <span class="myth-badge badge-myth">Myth</span>
              <div class="myth-text">"Cortisone injections are addictive and will make your joint worse immediately."</div>
            </div>
            <div class="myth-row">
              <span class="myth-badge badge-fact">Fact</span>
              <div class="myth-text">Cortisone itself is not chemically addictive. The concern is overuse — specifically, exceeding 3–4 injections per year in a single joint is where cartilage damage risk rises. Occasional, appropriately spaced cortisone injections are clinically safe and evidence-supported.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="myth-item">
            <div class="myth-row">
              <span class="myth-badge badge-myth">Myth</span>
              <div class="myth-text">"Hyaluronic acid injections work immediately — you should feel relief within a day."</div>
            </div>
            <div class="myth-row">
              <span class="myth-badge badge-fact">Fact</span>
              <div class="myth-text">HA injections have a gradual onset. Most patients begin to feel meaningful improvement between 2 and 6 weeks after the injection or final injection in a course. Expecting immediate relief leads to premature discontinuation of an otherwise effective treatment.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="myth-item">
            <div class="myth-row">
              <span class="myth-badge badge-myth">Myth</span>
              <div class="myth-text">"Injections will fix my arthritis — I won't need anything else."</div>
            </div>
            <div class="myth-row">
              <span class="myth-badge badge-fact">Fact</span>
              <div class="myth-text">Neither injection reverses structural arthritis or regrows cartilage. They manage symptoms and slow progression. They work best as part of a comprehensive programme including weight management, physiotherapy, nutritional correction, and activity modification.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="myth-item">
            <div class="myth-row">
              <span class="myth-badge badge-myth">Myth</span>
              <div class="myth-text">"If one injection didn't help, no injection will help."</div>
            </div>
            <div class="myth-row">
              <span class="myth-badge badge-fact">Fact</span>
              <div class="myth-text">Cortisone non-responders may respond well to HA, and vice versa. Each targets a different mechanism. Treatment failure with one does not predict failure with the other — a thorough reassessment of the pain driver should guide the next step.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="myth-item">
            <div class="myth-row">
              <span class="myth-badge badge-myth">Myth</span>
              <div class="myth-text">"I should avoid injections because they are dangerous and invasive."</div>
            </div>
            <div class="myth-row">
              <span class="myth-badge badge-fact">Fact</span>
              <div class="myth-text">When performed by a trained orthopaedic specialist using sterile technique and appropriate patient selection, both injections are extremely safe. The risks of untreated chronic pain — including prolonged NSAID use, muscle wasting, and psychological impact — often outweigh the risks of a well-indicated injection.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="section-divider"><div class="divider-icon">🏥</div></div>

      <!-- S7 -->
      <section class="article-section fade-up" id="procedure">
        <span class="section-tag">What to Expect</span>
        <h2>What Happens During & After the Injection?</h2>

        <p>Many patients feel anxious about joint injections, often imagining them as far more uncomfortable or complex than they are. Here is a clear picture of the process.</p>

        <ol class="steps-list">
          <li class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">01</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Assessment & Imaging Review</div>
              <p>Your orthopaedic specialist reviews your X-rays or MRI to confirm the grade of arthritis and select the appropriate injection. The injection site and patient position are determined based on the joint being treated.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">02</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Skin Preparation & Local Anaesthetic</div>
              <p>The skin over the injection site is cleaned thoroughly with antiseptic. A small amount of local anaesthetic may be applied to numb the area. For HA injections, this is often mixed directly with the HA formulation.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">03</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">The Injection (30–60 seconds)</div>
              <p>The needle is carefully guided into the joint space. If there is significant swelling, joint fluid may first be aspirated (removed) to create space and relieve pressure — this often provides immediate comfort. The medication is then injected. Most patients describe mild pressure rather than sharp pain.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">04</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Immediate Post-Injection (0–24 hours)</div>
              <p>Rest the treated joint for the remainder of the day. Avoid strenuous activity, heavy lifting, and prolonged walking. A mild aching or fullness in the joint is normal. Ice packs (20 minutes, 3–4 times) help reduce soreness. Do not apply heat.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">05</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Return to Normal Activity (Days 2–7)</div>
              <p>Light daily activities can typically resume after 48 hours. For cortisone, blood sugar monitoring should continue for 1–2 weeks in diabetic patients. For HA, gentle movement during the integration period (weeks 2–6) is encouraged to spread the gel through the joint space.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">06</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Follow-Up Assessment (4–8 weeks)</div>
              <p>Your response to the injection is reviewed. This determines whether a repeat injection is needed, whether a different treatment approach should be adopted, and how physiotherapy should be integrated going forward.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <div class="section-divider"><div class="divider-icon">🔄</div></div>

      <!-- S8 -->
      <section class="article-section fade-up" id="when-neither">
        <span class="section-tag">Beyond Injections</span>
        <h2>When Neither Injection Is the Right Answer</h2>

        <p>Both HA and cortisone are powerful tools — but they are not always the appropriate intervention. Knowing when to move beyond injections is as important as knowing which one to choose.</p>

        <div class="info-card navy">
          <div class="info-card-title">
            <div class="info-card-icon icon-navy">🚫</div>
            Situations Where Injections May Not Be Appropriate
          </div>
          <ul style="list-style:none; display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:12px;">
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.88rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--navy); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>End-stage arthritis (Grade 4):</strong> When cartilage is completely absent and bone rubs directly on bone, HA has limited benefit and the patient should be assessed for joint replacement</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.88rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--navy); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Active joint infection (septic arthritis):</strong> Injecting into an infected joint can be catastrophic — sterilisation and systemic antibiotics are the priority</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.88rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--navy); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Skin infection at the injection site:</strong> Proceeding through infected skin carries a serious risk of introducing bacteria into the joint</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.88rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--navy); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Planned surgery within 3 months:</strong> Both injections increase post-operative infection risk and should be avoided in this window</span>
            </li>
            <li style="display:flex; gap:12px; font-size:0.88rem; color:var(--text-lt);">
              <span style="color:var(--navy); font-weight:700; flex-shrink:0;">→</span>
              <span><strong>Uncontrolled blood clotting disorders or anticoagulant therapy:</strong> Requires careful haematological assessment before proceeding</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p>When injections are not appropriate or have been exhausted, other interventional options — including <strong>PRP (Platelet Rich Plasma) therapy</strong>, nerve blocks, prolotherapy, or joint replacement surgery — may be considered depending on the patient's clinical profile, age, and functional goals.</p>

        <div class="note-box">
          <div class="wb-icon">💡</div>
          <p>The decision between hyaluronic acid, cortisone, PRP, or surgical intervention should always be made through a thorough consultation — reviewing imaging, blood markers, functional assessment, and your personal health priorities together. <strong>No injection should be offered as a reflex without proper evaluation.</strong></p>
        </div>
      </section>

